<br>
One thing I would completely disagree on is root.  I'm lvl 63 and using root in PoP is useless.  It lasts approx one second on average for me.  I only use it to get far away enough from a mob to snare it.  This usually never works, as root never lasts long enough to run back a small bit and cast snare.  Wizard roots are one of the worst in the game imho.<br>
<br>
Snare, on the other hand, I use a lot.  In exp groups expecially on multi-pulls, just snare as the mobs are coming in, they're usually in a nice tight huddle while inc in my experience.  Then either trust your mezzer to stop them or kite them around the group until the are mezz parked.  Of course if you don't have a mezzer, then you or some other party member get to kite park them until they can be dealt with.<br>
<br>
Snare was the shiznitz in Seb, those darn frogs would run  nuts without it.  Enchanter would use ae mezz, and the situation was instantly under control.  Even if a resist or two, it's easier dealing with one resistant add than several adds at once that are beating on you, the cleric or the mezzer.<br>
<br>
Snare on a raid, I usually don't use it because there are usually enough classes to land single snares on even large pulls.  Exceptions would be if the raid snarer(s) are having trouble landing a snare, then I whip out the ole wizzie ae snare.  Usually our rangers are on snare, and if they are having trouble, they have a &quot;snare resisted&quot; hotkey and then wizzies break them out.  Although necros snares are pretty awesome, you can't mezz a dark'd mob <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :( --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/images/emoticons/frown.gif ALT=":("><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END-->  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#33333><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=faramir42>Faramir42</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Wizard</span><br>  Posts: 131<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/24/03 2:28 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wizards when they don't Nuke 101</span><hr size=1> Nice post Grimstaff, I agree with everything you suggest, mostly because I do all this stuff already. I've always been for pushing the limit to what wizards can do. <br>
<br>
Perception has been talked about lot on this site, as why a wizard could have a hard time getting a group. Doing all of these things will save the group. However, don't expect tons of praise for doing it. Simply because sometimes, there is to much going on for people to process everything. <br>
<br>
I don't know how many times I've made sure a close CH landed because I stunned the mob, giving the cleric the extra few seconds. I don't know how many times I've stopped a mobs CH when the group was seriously low on everything. And most of the time, I never got thanked. I've saved the enchanter and cleric with well placed roots on mobs that attacked them, giving them time to move away. <br>
<br>
My regular play group knows my value. When the second wizard is there, it's amazing how well we do as a group. My wizard friend and I have systems set up, where we can alternate who nukes and who stuns, effectivly keeping a mob immoble, while burning it down. On high end, hard casting mobs, together, we can keep a mob stunned and immoble while everyone else beats him down. <br>
<br>
In one case, to save the enchanter, I over nuked, since the other melees where having trouble getting aggro back. I got aggro, then concussioned the mob off me. By then the cleric was able to heal both me and the enchanter. By then, the melees had aggro, and down went the mob. <br>
<br>
Again, much of what we can do behind the scenes, is not going to get the praise of say a cleric that gets a CH just as the Tank is about to fall, or the enchanter that mezzes all the extra mobs.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub140.ezboard.com/bgraffeswizardcompilation.showUserPublicProfile?gid=mukaka>Mukaka</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Forum Apprentice</span><br>  Posts: 50<br> <font color=#ffffff>(6/24/03 2:57 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Wizards when they don't Nuke 101</span><hr size=1> I think there a good number of folks out there that enjoy a fun group even if it isn't at 100% efficiency. Nuke, nuke, concussion, nuke, nuke, concussion, ... is boring. Heal, heal, heal is even more boring. Hitting the &quot;special attacks&quot; hotkey repeatedly while tanking is boring. Have some fun and form a group without a tank.<br>
<br>
Not your thing? Then your group's efficiency is tied to your Cleric's ability to heal the tank. If the Cleric is running low on mana and you still have plenty, then by all means stun stun stun.<br>
<br>
If your Cleric/Enchanter dies, your group's efficiency is going to stink as the tank will likely go down and everyone loses their buffs. Stun the mob that's about to take down your healer/slower/tank. Root it and stand on top of the mob.<br>
<br>
Eye of Zomm/Tallon has definitely saved groups by scouting around the corner or behind a wall.<br>
<br>
Sometimes I know I'm going to gain agro (like when I'm testing for maximum chain nuking speed). When I do gain agro, I can either immediately stun/root the mob myself or announce beforehand the possibility of my agro draw.<br>
<br>
When ping-ponging mobs on purpose, I find the best way for the pinger to switch agro off the ponger is to nuke then stun until the mob turns.<br>
<br>
AE snare is a quick way to get all the extra pulls to agro you while your chanter has a chance to AE stun or mez them. AE DD could do the same thing, but I tend to have snare mem'd at all times.<br>
